<HEADLINE>
<P>
NEWSMAKERS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
Compiled by YEMI TOURE 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Tony Togs: Buckingham Palace on Sunday released the glamour photographs of 
Princess Di ahead of their publication in the December issue of British Vogue 
magazine. All the pictures -- taken by American photographer Patrick 
Demarchelier -- show her wearing off-the-shoulder evening dresses with a 
sophisticated, swept-back hairstyle and dark eye makeup. 
</P>
<P>
Lie Down: A group of London lawyers demonstrated last week what some people had 
long suspected -- they are Britain's best liars. The barristers easily snowed 
bankers, models, real estate agents and clergymen in a tournament of Perudo, a 
dice game in which players must lie to win. "I reserve my right to remain 
silent," said lawyer Clare Montgomery. "(Lying) is an essential life skill," 
said player Carl Hindmarch, a magazine editor. Whether the two were lying was 
not discussed. 
</P>
<P>
What Recession?: Celebrities fanned out over Beverly Hills during the 
Thanksgiving weekend, shopping for Christmas. At the posh Fred Hayman boutique 
on Rodeo Drive, Vanna White of TV's "Wheel of Fortune" bought a cocktail suit 
for her holiday parties in Aspen, and actress Jill St. John picked up presents 
for her first Christmas with Robert Wagner, whom she married in May. 
</P>
<P>
Maiden Flight: The hot trading card market, already booming with baseball, 
hockey, football, basketball, bowling and golf cards, is going into higher 
orbit. The Space-Shots series from a Gulfport, Miss., business pays tribute to 
Gus Grissom, Ed White and Roger Chaffee, who died in the launch-pad fire of the 
Apollo I spacecraft in 1967. The new business is being launched by Ed White 
III, son of the astronaut. 
</P>
