<HEADLINE>
<P>
NATION; 
</P>
<P>
SELF-FUNDED PLANS FREE OF STATES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
WASHINGTON 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Self-funded employee health care plans, which cover about 9.5 million working 
Americans, are not subject to state insurance laws and regulations, the Supreme 
Court ruled today. 
</P>
<P>
The court, by a 7-1 vote, said in the case of a seriously injured Pennsylvania 
teen-age girl that federal regulation of such plans preempts any state 
regulation. Self-funded plans have benefits paid directly by an employer and 
not purchased through an independent insurance company. 
</P>
</TEXT>
